Carnegie opens largest Indian
exibit east of Mississippi

Janet L. Syphan
Staff Writer

The Native American exhibit at the
Carnegie Museum of Natural History
used to consist of ﬁve or six glass cases
containing dark-skinned mannequins in
ceremonial poses.

One case ‘contained a Dakota war-
rior standing scantily—clad and scowl—
ing. Next to him, a Hopi Indian held a
snake in his mouth.

The cases displayed what most peo-
ple expected Indians to look and act
like.

But “these images are right out of
the worst John Wayne movie,” said
Lisa Mitten, a native Pittsburgher and
Mohawk Indian who works at Hillman
Library as a bibliographer.

Mitten was part in a consulting

a group for the urban section of the new

Alcoa Foundation Hall of American

' Indians at the Carnegie Museum, which

opened June 6.

The Alcoa Foundation Hall of
American Indians focuses on four
Indian nations: the Tlingit of the north-
west Coast, the Hopi of the Southwest,
the Lakota of the Plains, and the
Iroquois of the Northeast. Indians in
urban areas, particularly Pittsburgh,
also have a section in the Hall.

Not only did the museum consult
with 50 American Indians to create one
of the largest exhibits east of the
Mississippi, they also used casts from
living American Indians to create the
human ﬁgures in their dioramas —— a
scenic display of three—dimensional fig-
ures against a painted background.

The exhibit displays over 900 arti-
facts and several videos. Mitten said the
video of a powwow —— the gathering of
various tribes to share in singing, danc-
ing and renewing friendships ——
reminded her of watching an old home
movie. When local American Indians
came to the museum and watched it,

they recognized people they knew.

The exhibit also contains computer I

activities and a planetarium-style show
about how the stars and universe affect-
ed American Indian life.

The museum owned most of the
artifacts displayed, although they used 1

few of them in the previous Indian -

exhibit, said Sandra Lepri of the
Carnegie. '
She said this had to do with the lack .

of space in the museum, a condition ;

that left Native Americans under repre-
sented and incorrectly depicted.
“The old exhibit was something I

never wanted to take my kids to see,” i

Mitten said. “It was insulting.”

She described the Hopi Snake
Dance display as “misleading,” saying
it, as well as other displays, gave view-
ers inaccurate and sensationalized ideas

about Native American people and their Y I r

culture. A

“The museum displayed the arti-
facts without describing what they were
used for,” she said. “They were taken
out of context.” «

Dr. Pamela Soeder, a Muskogee’
Creek Indian and professor at Slippery
Rock, also worked with the consulting
group. She agreed with Mitten.

“Children walked away from that.
exhibit with confirmed stereotypes,”
she said. i

The Museum said they realized the ,
previous display did not represent
American Indians accurately.

“There were certain thoughts and
perceptions cast upon American
Indians,” Lepri said. “Everyone dis-
played American Indians from the
white persons’ perspective, not just
museums, but photographers, writers
and the entire society.”

Soeder, who teaches classes focus-
ing on cultural diversity, said she hopes
the Hall will dispel any misconceptions
people have formed because of the

