  , UPMC awarded

$7.7 million

research grant

The University of Pittsburgh
Medical Center has the world’s largest
liver transplant program, and a $7.7 mil-
lion grant from the National Cancer
Institute (NCI) will help UPMC
researchers to further reﬁne the trans-
plant procedure and to study possible
vaccines for cancer.

“This funding provides us an
unprecedented opportunity to expand
our studies of dendritic cell biology and
its performance in disease,” said Dr.
Michael T. Lotze, lead investigator on
the grant; professor of surgery and mole-
cular genetics and biochemistry; and co-
director of the University of Pittsburgh
Cancer Institute’s Biological
Therapeutics Program.

Dendritic cells travel throughout
the body, identifying invading viruses
and bacteria and stimulating the immune
system to attack those invaders.

“We have a unique gathering of
internationally recognized investigators
who are exploring dendritic cell—based

. therapies at a time when the isolation,
» L culture and application of these cells to

human disease have progressed signiﬁ-
cantly,” Lotze said.

The grant will give researchers
money to study ways to increase liver-
transplant tolerance, and will fund ﬁve

* other projects at UPMC.

One project will focus on develop-
ing a cancer vaccine using dendritic cells
as a base. Another will attempt to genet-
ically modify dendritic cells so they
would ﬁght cancer. A third project will
search for a way to_develop a dendritic
cell—based vaccine speciﬁcally for lung
cancer.

A fourth project will focus on the
importance of dendritic cells in a mouse
model of diabetes, and a ﬁfth will focus
on how dendritic cells stimulate auto-
immunity in scleroderma, an abnormal
hardening or thickening of the skin.

The University of Pittsburgh
Cancer Institute is one of 31 NCI-desig-
nated comprehensive cancer centers.

