Frank described the tornado as a
big brown swirling mass of twirling
debris.

“It’s not like what you picture,” he
said. “You don’t see the funnel, just the
effects.”

As quickly as it had come, the
twister left. The sky suddenly cleared
up.

One of the few lucky residents of
Mt. Washington who had phone service
through the storm, Frank said he began
to realize how widespread the damage
was after receiving a call from his
father, who lives several blocks away.
While his house suffered practically no
damage, except for a neighbor’s tree
that fell into his yard, it became clear to
him very quickly that not everyone had
been so lucky.

“It’s a miracle no one was killed,”
he said. “That was sheer luck, with the
amount of damage, ﬂying signs and
ﬂying debris.”

Frank said he left his house and
started walking down Virginia Avenue,
which he said was “basically trashed.”

As the realization that the damage
in human terms could have been far
worse sank in, Frank said there was
“kind of a festive air — everyone sort
of having fun.” The mood was further
lightened when several stores, having
lost their electricity, started to give

away their stocks of ice cream.

Police had not yet arrived to deal
with the traffic problems on the
blocked roadways, so Frank directed
trafﬁc on McArdle Roadway for about
20 minutes until they arrived.

The helpful spirit of neighbors was
given many chances to shine through
that night, he said. -

“It was amazing the little acts of
heroism you found,” Frank. said.
“Private citizens were helping to close
roads, letting people use their cell
phones to call their family and tell then
they were O.K. There was a real sense
of community spirit. I really think it’s a
Pittsburgh thing.”

In the days that followed, many
storm victims would praise the men
and women involved in the cleanup,
according to Frank.

“It was amazing what a wonderful
job the city workers did, especially
Public Works,” he said. “After a couple
of days, it looked like nothing hap-
pened. All these tourists are coming up
now, and there’s nothing to see.”

Frank said he believes people real-
ize it could have been much worse. And
many hope that valuable lessons have
been learned in case of future emergen-
cies. Frank has a very simple starting
point.

“The number one lesson I learned
from this is to get a radio with a bat-
tery,” he said. “And candles are a good
thing.”

