Violence not a viable answer ;

Whether from physics class or the night
they got drunk for the first time, many stu-
dents learn a lot when they come to college.
Thefe is different knowledge to be gained
from each experience, though. Just because
one accumulates knowledge does not neces-
sarily mean he understands it or can use it.
Life provides us with infinite situations to
remind us of that.

Take an event that occurred last summer.

when I was travelling. At a downtown bas-
ketball court, I witnessed two teenagers,
about 16 years old, playing one-on-one. One,
who we’ll call Mike, was quite drunk and
very unhappy that he bet his bus fare home
/on the game. Quite predictably,
Mike lost the game to the other
player, who we’ll call Tom.
That’s when the real trouble
began. Mike, who was whining
about how he had no money to get
home and how Tom was a jerk for taking his
money, wandered a little too close to Tom

and got shoved. Out of the blue, Torn went

nuclear on him. I realize that at 16 you react
differently to insults than you might six years
later, but Mike was drunk and no threat to
anyone but himself. But Torn started swear-
ing athim and declared he wanted to fight.

I think Mike realized things were out of
control and that he had made a mistake. He
made an effort to cool things down as Tom
stripped off his jacket and went into a
boxer’s stance, ﬁring punches in the air.
Then Tom slapped his hand away and sud-
denly pulled out a knife. He threatened to
stab Mike, claiming the knife had already
been used several times. Mind you, this was
the player who was not drunk. Tom eventu-
ally wound down and others rushed in, send-
ing both of them home. Who wants to play
with a guy who might stab you?

This was a case where I had all the infor-
mation but couldn’t understand it. Tom went
from winning a basketball game to nearly
stabbing his opponent, a person who was not
a threat and hadn’t blatantly insulted him.
This was the first time Tom and Mike had
met, so there was no history of bad blood.
Tom didn’t even try to talk things out, feel-
ing that for some reason his only option was
violence.

Not only do I not understand this men-
tality, I can’t even begin to comprehend it. I

ANDREW

MILLER

 

know emotions hold more sway for
teenagers, but this went beyond a normal
teenage reaction. This was challenging a
drunk to a ﬁght for no real reason, even
though you know you’d beat him to a pulp.
Furthermore, why face jail time and ruin
your life for stabbing a drunk person?

The problem is that this is not an isolat-
ed incident. I’ve witnessed ﬁghts break out
time and time again, no matter what city I’ve
played in. Fists begin ﬂying over scores, in
cases where it’s just a matter of some ele-
mentary addition. People wind up choking
each other over some inadvertent foul. The
game simply isn’t fun anymore when you
have to wonder whether your
opponent might take a swing or a
stab at you out of frustration.

Animosity is something that
naturally builds up between oppo-
nents, especially in sports with
physical contact. And if you’ve ever played
in the low post going for a rebound, with
elbows ﬂying and some guy climbing your
back, you know it can be war. But it’s sup-
posed to end with the whistle or the action. If
I could build a house with all my bricks, put
out an APB for my defense, or am frustrated
over a lack of teamwork, is my opponent to
blame for it? How is hitting him going to
help matters?

If somebody has problems with violence
on the basketball court, how do they handle
real problems elsewhere, with other people?
Is violence the only option there as well?
Where does it end? I realize I bring a white,
suburban outlook to all of this, but it seems
there have to be better alternatives to always
ﬁghting or potentially being in trouble with
the law.

Maybe that’s the problem. Maybe I just
don’t understand what everyone else is
bringing to the table, that perhaps there’s
some code that allows for any issue to be
resolved with violence. But to me, it’s just
sad that a 16-year-old kid feels like poten-
tially ruining his life over something as sim-
ple as basketball. It becomes tragic when one
considers violence could be the only option
for a generation of inner-city youth.

Andrew Miller wonders how you’re sup-
posed to ﬁx or help what you don ’t under-
stand.

