out” and joke about the game of “hide the
salami.” Furthermore, the two activities are
remarkably similar”. all the licking and suck-
ing seem almost like vain attempts to eat
ﬂesh. In fact, it surprises me that we so infre-
quently hear about incidents of cannibalism,
given the similarity of the two appetites.
Some time ago, I wondered why the
hunger strike was such a common form of
protest, though the sex strike was virtually
unheard of. One suffers whether starving for
food or starving for sex, and the protest is
somehow connected to the suﬂering, I ﬁg-
ured. Recalling my New Year’s resolution to
“ rforrn at least one noble deed” I cleverly
decided that a sex strike would adequately
fulﬁll my quota. So far as I could tell, a gen-
uine hunger strike had to be associated with
some cause, otherwise it was ordinarily
called a diet (this observation raised an etlri-
cal concern: is it OK for a hunger-striker to
take hunger-suppression pills? Probably
not, since, like I said, the protest and pain are
connected in some way). _
,1 Choosing .a cause was easier than I
thought it would be. The main criterion for
a noble cause is that it be subjective instead
of objective; the question to ask is not “Do
my actions in fact aifect a situation for the
better?” but rather, “Does it make me feel

good to think that my efforts are better-
intentioned than anyone else’s?” “With this in
mind, I decided on “social justice” as my
cause -— the vaguer the cause, the better.

. Feeling more noble than usual, I
embarked on my sex strike. I expected some
cold critic to point out that my life was pro-
ceeding in no discernibly different way, to
whom I would reply, “Yes, but now my suf-
fering is focused on a noble intention — my
previously idle pains now reach out from
my mind into the world” The same cold
critic, that bitter skeptic, might have sug-
gested that my cause bordered on nonsense.

Well in that case, I did have a particular
and appropriate form of social justice in
mind. Egalitarians of all kinds have long
complained about material inequality (call-
ing it “inequity” with a slick categorical
hop), yet have failed to address sexual
inequality. However, it is just as clear to me
that the distribution of sex in this country is
unequal. One need only consider the case of
the successful rock star, that robber baron of
the sexual world, to recognize this inequali-
ty. From inequality, it only takes the con-_
struction of an ideal ——- e.g. that every per-
son should get laid daily — to yield an
inequity. “So it is the vast sexual inequity in
the world against which my sex strike is a

protest,” I would have replied to the mean-
spirited skeptic.

Whilst enduring the sex strike, I had the
opportunity to contemplate the origins of
sexual inequity. There is, of course, the gen-
eral prudishness for which contemporary
watered-down Christianity — Christ Lite
— is to blame. The thrust of that ideology is
that sex outside rigidly deﬁned circum-
stances is patently bad; some reckless nooky
will probably earn you some time in purga-
tory, maybe a m‘enage ‘a trois will get you
to hell (don’t quote me on the specifics).
Then there are the “AIDS is the Black
Death” crisis-mongers who have inspired
new heights of self-righteousness (“where’s
your red ribbon, you reactionary?!”) and
who have spread enough disinformation to
keep many of us sexually deprived for years
to conre. Both inﬂuences, as well as others,
have contributed to the emergence of a vast
class of sexually underprivileged people.

My sex strike has been over for some
time now, but I encourage others to adopt
such forms of resistance to protest what is a
sorry, unbearable and inhumane situation.

