If the music critics ever found a
way to pin down Beck as either a folkie,
a hip-hop maven, a psychedelic popster
or all three genres rolled into one, they
would be writing obituaries by now.

It’ s a major sport among rock
scribes to pigeonhole artists into a
genre, but they can't actually corral
Beck's sound. His evasion of the fences
and restraints makes him a major fave
among music writers and fans.

Pittsburgh will certainly have a
chance to see the one-narned wun-
derkind when he comes to Coca-Cola
Star Lake Amphitheatre in support of
his newest multi-platinum album,
Odelay. When you catch him live, four

words come to mind — never a dull

. moment.

A live Beck show is full of humor
and strong live material, as well as other
surprises. Hopping along for the
Pittsburgh stop will be southem-fried
piano geeks Ben Folds Five, who
breathe the spirit of ’70’ s angst and
Todd Rundgren into their gold-selling
Epic debut, Whatever and Ever, Amen.

It’ s that all-over-the-place musical
mentality that makes Beck a revered
modern rock artist on the radio and
with the fans.

Spin recently named him as the
most vital artist of the '90s, beating out
the likes of Radiohead and Alanis
Morrissette. .

Odelay, released in 1997, won two
Grammy Awards and spawned several
hits including: ”Where It’ s At,” ”Devil’s
Haircut,” ”The New Pollution,” and

”]ackass.”

