they need to call a penalty every once in a
while.

In the playoffs two years ago, the
Penguins were playing the Washington
Capitals, who are in the ﬁnals this year.
What a joke that is. They have no talent and
are not exciting at all.

During one particular series the Caps
played in this year, Don Koharski, an NHL
veteran official, had one of his worst days
ever. He has never really done his job well,
but the Sabres—Caps game six will be

remembered for a long time.

In the third period, he awarded a
ridiculous power play to the Capitals who
had a very tough time at the beginning of
the game. In the third, the Sabres had two
odd-man rushes against the Capitals’ ﬂoun-
dering defense. Washington thwarted both
rushes by blatantly pulling down Sabres on
their way to the goal cage.

These actions by the Capitals would be
considered assault and battery in any other
part of American society, but Koharski did
not think they warranted a penalty.

Just seconds after the bogus non-calls,
the Capitals scored on the power play and
earned their ﬁrst ever trip to the Stanley
Cup Finals. They should give a ring to Don
Koharski if they do win the Cup.

In the immortal words of Jim
Schoenfeld, “Hey Koharski, you fat pig.
Go eat another donut.” This is what the
game is coming to. Mediocre teams okay
for the most coveted and tradition—1aden
trophy in sports.

The NHL has alienated fans, but it has
also lost the support of the players.
Lernieux, one of the best players of all time,
left the sport, citing the officiating and the
lack of excitement in the game as reasons
for leaving. He says he has not watched a
game on TV since he retired because it is so
boring.

Also, Brett Hull torched league oili-
cials with his comments earlier this year
about how boring the league has become.

Betteman and the NHL have a perfect
chance to take the spotlight with Michael
Jordan apparently leaving basketball along
with that sport’s imminent trouble. The
league should get its act together in order to
gain the notoriety it so desperately wants.

Patrick Robertson is the sports editor
for the Pitt News and doesn’t say these
things only because he is a Penguins ’ fan.
he really wants to see hockey step into the
spotlight so that everyone can see what a
great sport it is.

