New bowl system
announced

The Bowl Championship Series, or
the entity formerly known as the Bowl
Alliance, has announced its plans for
the 1998 bowl lineup.

It will use the Associated Press and
ESPN/U SA Today polls in conjunction
with an objective entity which will take
into account strength of schedule and
strength of opponents’ schedule to
decide who should play in the national
championship game of college football.

This new system still leaves ques-
tions with regards to more than two
undefeated teams, zero undefeated
teams, or the possibility of several
teams with one only loss. ‘

The new bowl lineups and BCS
guidelines should be released soon, so
look to The Pitt News in the coming
weeks to help you sort through the
muddled bowl picture.

KQV acquires
radio rights

The University of Pittsburgh has
given the radio broadcast rights of foot-
ball games and men’s basketball games
this fall to KQV—AM (1410).

KQV lured the rights away from
WTAE (1250), who has held them for
the past 28 years.

WTAE also lost the rights to broad-
cast Pittsburgh Penguins games this
year, just a few months after changing
to an all—sports format. WTAE is
scrambling to get the rights for some
local sports.

Bill Hillgrove will keep his job as
play-by—play man for the football and
basketball teams while negotiations are
underway for his color man.

KQV is owned by Pinnacle Sports
Productions, an Omaha, Neb. based
company that also holds the rights to
University of Nebraska games.

